Turkey is broadening diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey tried to join the European Union, the European powers were anxious to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern part of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps in Asia, lies one of the most beautiful relics of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in neo-Renaissance style.
That's at least what the tour guides tell you.
The building is straddling between the end of the platforms with a tower on each of its corners looking at the world as some provincial German municipalities.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slightly decadent.
But once inside the ticket office from the vaulted ceiling, there is no doubt about the size of the enterprise of what was the most western passage.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a retard to the imperial game, wanted to fulfil its ambitions to dominate the Middle East through this railroad that ran in Damascus, Baghdad and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperial ambitions sank during the First World War.
His railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
Its isolation from the surrounding region, generated by the icy borders of the Cold War, has passed
British and ruling forces advanced out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for Hyderpasha station, too.
In 1917 a munitions train exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then it has slowly gone into disrepair, largely overtaken by history.
But nowadays, this railway outlet for Anatolia and all the points to the east serve - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's ever greater diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - AKP - has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
Its isolation from its surrounding regions, generated by the icy borders of the Cold War, has passed.
Now there is a new policy of commitment.
The Turkish Government has a remarkable relationship with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to estimate the parameters of this new foreign policy, I embarked on the bed car for the Turkish capital Ankara, visiting one of the main foreign policy experts of AKP, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a rush along the slopes that produced the cadences from the ancient world of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - proposed as a new city for a secular state intent on turning its back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamic roots represents an exemplary shift in the Turkish consensus.
He suggested some suspicions in the West, more notably in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern structure of stone and steel - built ad hoc - in a developing suburb, surrounded by medium-built shopping centers and pastry shops of power, where managers in business suits - both men and women - meet to make early-morning contracts.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost every other political party in Europe.
Complete, tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry, too.
"The purpose of the foreign policy party is now to reintegrate Turkey with its closest neighbours.
The Cold War was an anomaly, "he says.
Turkey has been cut off from its hinterland.
Today he has to look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't the case with one or the other.
They must be both.
"But surely at some point," I ask, "will Turkey be forced to decide?"
"Turkey," he says, "does not want to face that choice."
Then he points out one point that almost everyone I have spoken to here has recited by heart: the links between the Middle East and the Caucasus, and all around the Black Sea, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, Europe as a whole can metaphorically travel those railway lines eastwards through Asia and the Middle East.
Once again at Hydarpasha station, after another night in white, I think of those two German gentlemen Herr Ritter and Herr Conu who had watched this building built 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to find that Europe's medium-eastern ambitions can now largely be in the hands of Turkey.
And while I wait at the terminal for the ferry that takes me back through the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey has always been called "the sick man of Europe."
Then at least there seemed to be no doubt about which continent should make demands on this fascinating country.
