The "bee car" to avoid collisions
As part of the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, and in particular by bees.
The Japanese society has created a robot that, taking for example the flight of bees, knows how to avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Advanced Technical Center of Nissan Motor Co. have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research of the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, BR23C constitutes an extension of the Security Shield of four areas produced by Nissan.
This robot is intended to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the manufacturer's vehicles.
During the flight, each bee creates its own space of oval shape which is very similar to the Nissan security shield.
But the most important thing is the compound eyes of the bees, able to see in all directions with an angle above 300 degrees, and that allow the insect to fly without interruption in his personal space.
To recreate this visual functionality, engineers have developed what they have defined as a Laser Range Finder.
This mechanism identifies the obstacles facing the BR23C for a radius within two metres and a maximum width of 180 degrees, calculates the distance from the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor that immediately prevents collision.
"At the moment when it detects an obstacle, the small robot mimics the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning on the wheels at right or greater angle to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot divert upwards or downwards, or even diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which it can turn its wheels and not take infinite directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid collisions.
"This device just needs to process information every few seconds, and act from this data.
It does not require the storage of information or the intuitive logic of prior maneuvers, so it can work without interruption and with only a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise you, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, nor mega. "
This is the first step towards the development of new technologies for instantaneous collision prevention, a technology Nissan hopes will be standard in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium ion type.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of units with a GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to the destination avoiding obstacles in the path.
