Rafael Correa à Quito, ce lundi.
Establish the republic on a socialism right in the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
On Sunday, following the example of colleagues and friends, it was the latter who gave voice to the draft of a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since, according to official results, 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, on an 80% vote basis.
According to these results, the "no" was 28%, while 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% blank cards.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, it should get half the votes, plus one.
On Sunday, two polls at the polling stations and an estimate of a non-governmental organization had announced an overwhelming victory of "yes," placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa also claimed the victory of his draft Constitution on the night between Sunday and Monday.
The "Constitution triumphed gloriously," he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians in the Guayaquil Governorate, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As always, Chávez and Morales congratulated Rafael Correa, as did his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The ballot, which took place calmly according to the election observation mission of the Organization of American States (OEA), was based on a text of 444 points to consolidate the "new socialism" defended by the President.
This draft Constitution consecrates the power of the state over the economy, reserving to it the "development planning" of a country that lives essentially from the oil extraction carried out by large foreign companies and consequently of their currency.
Conceived by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also gives greater power to the Head of State, who can be elected for two consecutive mandates of four years, to have the opportunity to dissolve the assembly.
Correa has already announced its intention to use this amendment and to re-propose its candidacy for a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also states the gratuitousness of health and education services, which the President has begun to promote in this country of 13,9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also prohibits the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington on the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US drug operations.
